# Android Website Breakage Investigations

Use this for Android browser bugs where a live website behaves differently in DuckDuckGo than expected.

## Environment

Use an attached real device for the primary reproduction when one is available in `adb devices`. If no real device is available, say so and use an emulator.

Use an emulator when:

- no real device is attached to the agent host
- testing a specific Android or WebView version matrix
- isolating emulator-only behavior
- avoiding changes to a shared physical device

```sh
adb devices
adb shell getprop ro.build.version.sdk
adb shell getprop ro.product.cpu.abilist
adb shell dumpsys webviewupdate
```

Record:

- device or emulator name
- Android API level
- active WebView package and version
- GPU mode
- exact URL and user action

## Emulator GPU mode

For WebView rendering investigations, start the emulator with software GL:

```sh
emulator -avd <avd-name> -no-window -gpu swangle_indirect -no-snapshot -no-boot-anim
```

Avoid `swiftshader_indirect` unless the task is specifically comparing graphics backends; it can introduce emulator instability that is unrelated to the site.

## Installing alternate WebView versions

System images often bundle old WebView versions. To test Beta, Dev, or Canary, sideload a compatible Google-signed APK for the emulator or device ABI.

Check compatibility first:

```sh
adb shell getprop ro.product.cpu.abilist
adb shell getprop ro.build.version.sdk
```

Install and select the provider:

```sh
adb install -r /tmp/webview-provider.apk
adb shell cmd webviewupdate set-webview-implementation <package-name>
adb shell dumpsys webviewupdate
adb shell am force-stop com.duckduckgo.mobile.android.debug
```

Provider package names:

```text
Stable: com.google.android.webview
Beta:   com.google.android.webview.beta
Dev:    com.google.android.webview.dev
Canary: com.google.android.webview.canary
```

If the selected provider does not change, confirm the APK signature, ABI, min SDK, and target SDK are valid for the device.

## Reproduction fidelity

Use real user input for the primary repro. DevTools-driven navigation can skip site event handlers or user-activation paths.

```sh
adb shell wm size
adb shell input tap <x> <y>
adb shell input swipe <x1> <y1> <x2> <y2> <duration-ms>
```

`adb shell input` uses physical screen coordinates. Screenshots may be scaled in the chat UI, so check `wm size` before calculating taps.

Use DevTools for inspection and controlled follow-up tests, not as the first reproduction path.

## Screenshots

Capture before and after the action:

```sh
adb exec-out screencap -p > /tmp/site-before.png
adb exec-out screencap -p > /tmp/site-after.png
```

Compare:

- address bar URL
- visible page content
- loading indicator
- overlays, consent dialogs, and interstitials
- whether user input changes the visible state

## Logging

Clear logs immediately before the action:

```sh
adb logcat -c
```

Capture app-scoped logs:

```sh
pid=$(adb shell pidof com.duckduckgo.mobile.android.debug | tr -d '\r')
adb logcat -d --pid "$pid" -v time | rg \
  "BrowserWebViewClient|BrowserChromeClient|onPageStarted|onPageFinished|onProgressChanged|shouldOverride|Renderer|RenderProcess|WEB_VIEW"
```

Record callback order and timestamps alongside screenshots. A useful report states what the page did visually and what the browser believed happened.

## WebView DevTools

Find and forward the WebView DevTools socket:

```sh
adb shell cat /proc/net/unix | rg webview_devtools
pid=$(adb shell pidof com.duckduckgo.mobile.android.debug | tr -d '\r')
adb forward tcp:9222 localabstract:webview_devtools_remote_$pid
curl http://127.0.0.1:9222/json/list
```

Use DevTools to inspect:

- current URL and title
- DOM state
- console errors
- network activity
- link targets and event handlers

Do not rely on `location.href = ...` or synthetic DOM clicks as the only reproduction evidence.

## Minimum investigation summary

Include:

- device/emulator, API level, GPU mode
- WebView provider package and version
- tested URL and exact user action
- whether the issue reproduces with real input
- before/after screenshots
- relevant callback timeline
- whether reload, back/forward, app background/foreground, or user input changes the state
- differences from a lightweight control page, if tested
